title: Notre Dame girls soccer team gets important win over 'iconic' Northwestern
text:
Complete Box Score Â» 
No matter the season, Northwestern always seems to be near the top of the Colonial League girls soccer standings. 
That's why Notre Dame coach Sue Aquilina was so happy with her team's 2-0 road win over the Tigers on Tuesday night. Sue Aquilina (Courtesy Photo) 
"It's a very important win because I don't remember the last time we were able to beat Northwestern," Aquilina said. "This is like an icon in girls soccer. Anyone that competes strongly against Northwestern, any coach is going to be proud of that. So I'm very proud of the girls today." 
For Notre Dame goalkeeper M'Kenna Murphy and the other 10 seniors on the team, the victory over the Tigers was a special one. 
"Since I've been here, we've never beat Northwestern," Murphy said. "So this is very big for our seniors." 
She made eight saves, including a few leaping ones, to make sure Notre Dame would finally get the win over the perennial power. 
"We all came in very pumped, very hyped, knowing that we had to play our best in this game and we all left it all out there. And that is why as a team, we got this win," Murphy said. 
"I expected a very difficult game. I think we all did, which is why we all worked very hard in practice and it showed out here today," Murphy added. "We all worked well together and we all played our very best. We deserved this win."
